description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure. A head, probably of Hera, broken from a figure. Her hair is parted in the centre and is drawn back beneath a large plain diadem. The hair is not indicated behind the diadem, and she probably wears a himation veiled over it, the fall of which remains on the right side of her neck. She has summarily modelled earrings. Hollow, from two-piece mould and made probably with the body, rather than added and the diadem is applied. Traces of an overall white dressing, scientific analysis shows it to be gypsum, with specks of red paint by the left eye and on the hair on the right; pinkish-orange paint behind the diadem. Brown Nile silt with common fine gold mica, quartz and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of seated youth. A youth: the front part only, the back roughly flat. He is seated on a block or stool with his forearms resting on his thighs, the hands placed on each side of his large thick projecting phallus. The hairline above his brow is indicated by a groove, but his head is shown as though shaved except for a large side-lock curling onto his right shoulder; the ears are large. The block on which he sits widens into a low plinth on each side.  Pressed into a one-piece mould, with sparse traces of white coating and pink paint on neck, phallus and legs. Orange-brown Nile silt with a drab surface and abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Terracotta reclining ithyphallic figure.  A reclining naked man, his head lost and his legs extending to his right, the left bent and close to the ground, the right with the knee raised (the right leg below the knee is missing, as is the left foot). He leans his left elbow and forearm on a pile of cushions, and his right hand holds his large phallus upright against his right side, but its end is broken off. His left hand is flaked away, but was held against his corpulent belly, perhaps holding an object.   The figure is modelled in relief with an intended flat back and was probably made in a one-piece mould; it has a flat-faced plinth, hollowed out underneath, much of which is lost on the figure’s right side. There are minute traces of a white dressing.

description.value: Bronze figure of Bastet: this solid cast figure of the goddess Bastet represents her as a woman with cat's head wearing a heavily patterned long garment. Her eyes have gold inlays and her ears are pierced for earrings. Of all the maned lion goddesses who were revered for their ferocity, Bastet alone was later transformed into the less terrible cat. The female cat was particularly noted for her fecundity, and so Bastet was adored as goddess of fertility and, with less obvious logic, of festivity and intoxication. As evidence of her fecundity no less than four kittens sit at her feet. Another perches inside the sistrum or Egyptian rattle, which she carries in her hand to symbolize the other facet of her personality, for it is a musical instrument connected with merrymaking. Originally there were two horizontal rods inside the hoop bearing metal discs intended to make a clashing sound when the instrument was shaken. The face of the goddess Hathor, who was also connected with music, appears on the sistrum's handle. Across her chest Bastet carries an aegis or broad collar, surmounted by a lion goddess' head wearing a sun disc, perhaps representing Bastet herself in her original fierce manifestation. The 'aegis' is probably to be interpreted as the top of the counterpoise to a 'menyet' collar of loosely strung beads, another musical instrument connected with merrymaking; when shaken the beads would clack together. There is a hieroglyphic text around the edges of the plinth, largely eroded or erased.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of a woman seated on a rock. The woman is wearing a long chiton and wrapped in a large himation, which completely covers her bent right arm and hand, although her hand gathers an end of the himation, which falls in narrow folds over her left thigh. Her left hand, which emerges from the himation, is placed in her lap. She has a central parting in her hair and wears a sakkos on the back of her head, its tail hanging down her back; the head is bent to her right and she looks slightly down. At the rear, the rock is modelled, but the woman’s back is plain, with a large almost circular vent. Hollow, from a two-piece mould with added mould-made head. Traces of an overall white dressing, covered in places with the remains of a creamy-yellow paint on parts of the himation. Light-brown clay, probably a Nile silt, but perhaps mixed with another clay, with abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure. Head broken from the figure of an actor playing a slave character in the New Comedy. Actor's mask indicated by a raised edge around chin and head, with the actor's own hair showing below. The hair of the mask is peaked at the front and combed back on the top and each side; there is a large trumpet-mouth, heavy eyebrows and a furrowed forehead.  The method of manufacture is uncertain: it is solid, probably made in a two-piece mould, with any traces of mould-lines obscured by considerable subsequent hand-tooling of the surface. The head was then added to its (now) lost body before firing.  Traces of an overall white dressing and pink paint on shin and black details around the eyes. Red-brown Nile silt with frequent fine gold mica, white and quartz inclusions.

She stands leaning forward slightly, and inclined even more so to her right, producing a distinct crease at waist level on her right side. The breasts are not large, and a tiny twist of clay in the pubic area must be fortuitous on a female body: it does not represent male genitals and we do not have Hermaphrodite here. description.value: Fragmentary limestone figure of a naked female, the head, lower arms and feet now lost.  The female figure is depicted in a standing position with the legs placed close together and the arms held by the sides of the body. The figure is nude with clear modelling of the full bust, wide hips, and slightly swollen belly. The elongated hands and fingers are placed flat against the upper thighs. A broad collar depicted in relief adorns her neck, with a counterpoise indicated on the back. Traces of red paint detail the additional jewellery worn by the figure, including rings on the fingers, bracelets around her upper arms and wrists, a long beaded necklace extending down to the torso, and a belted girdle worn high on the hips with lotus flowers depicted on the ends of the material, both falling onto the upper thigh. On the reverse, the girdle features a large wedjat eye of Horus.
